# **10\. Grafana Observability — UI Application**

The Django application ships logs, traces, and metrics to Grafana Cloud over OTLP/HTTP. Observability is wired once in sql\_license\_optimizer/observability.py and activated at server startup — no manual instrumentation is required in individual views or services.

## **10.1  Startup & Initialisation**

| Step | What Happens | File |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Django app fully loads (LOGGING dictConfig runs, all handlers registered) | wsgi.py / asgi.py |
| 2 | configure\_observability() called immediately after — must be after step 1 or OTLP handler is overwritten by dictConfig | observability.py |
| 3 | LoggerProvider, TracerProvider, and MeterProvider created with shared resource attributes and registered as global providers | observability.py |
| 4 | \_TruncatingHandler attached to root, optimizer, django, and django.request loggers — all app log records now flow to Loki | observability.py |
| 5 | DjangoInstrumentor().instrument() auto-instruments all Django HTTP request handling — traces and HTTP metrics created automatically | observability.py |

## **10.2  Three Signal Pipelines**

| Signal | Grafana Product | Export Endpoint | What Is Sent |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| Logs | Loki | /v1/logs | Every logger.\* call across the app — view calls, agent calls, errors, fallback triggers, request lifecycle |
| Traces | Tempo | /v1/traces | One span per HTTP request. Nested child spans where DjangoInstrumentor can detect them. Linked by trace\_id to Loki entries. |
| Metrics | Prometheus | /v1/metrics | Auto: HTTP request count, latency histogram, active requests (from DjangoInstrumentor). Custom: any instrument created via get\_meter(). |

## **10.3  Key Components**

| Component | File | Purpose |
| :---- | :---- | :---- |
| configure\_observability() | sql\_license\_optimizer/observability.py | Main wiring function. Creates all three providers, attaches OTLP exporters, runs DjangoInstrumentor. Called once per worker process. |
| \_TruncatingHandler | sql\_license\_optimizer/observability.py | Custom LoggingHandler that truncates messages exceeding 200 KB before sending to Loki (Loki rejects entries \> 262 KB). Works on a copy — console and file handlers still receive the full message. |
| get\_meter(name) | sql\_license\_optimizer/observability.py | Factory for OTEL Counters and Histograms. Safe to call before configure\_observability() — returns a no-op meter if OTLP is not configured. |
| RequestIdMiddleware | optimizer/middleware.py | Generates a 12-character UUID for every incoming request. Stores it in a ContextVar and appends it to the X-Request-ID response header. |
| RequestIdFilter | optimizer/middleware.py | Logging filter attached to the root logger. Stamps request\_id on every LogRecord so all log lines for a request share the same ID in Loki. |
| PiiRedactingFilter | optimizer/middleware.py | Regex-redacts email addresses from log messages and structured extra fields. Attached separately to console, file handlers, and the OTLP handler to cover all three destinations. |
| JsonFormatter | optimizer/logger.py | Formats each log record as a single JSON line. Includes trace\_id and span\_id when emitted inside an active OTEL span, enabling direct Loki → Tempo correlation. |
| DailyLevelFileHandler | optimizer/logger.py | Writes logs to logs/YYYY-MM-DD/\<level\>.log with daily rotation. Used in development (LOG\_TO\_FILES=true). Not used in production — OTLP export handles prod log shipping. |

